## Core mental model (always true)

- **The persistence context is a first-level cache + unit of work.** Within one context, the same
  row maps to **one** entity instance (identity guarantee). It tracks changes and is per-tx /
  per-`EntityManager`, never shared across threads.
- **Entity states:** *transient* (new, no id, untracked) → *managed* (attached to a context, dirty
  tracking on) → *detached* (context closed / `clear`ed — still has identity, no longer tracked) →
  *removed*. `persist` makes transient managed; `merge` copies a detached state into a managed copy;
  `find`/queries return managed entities.
- **Dirty checking + flush-on-commit:** you mutate a *managed* entity and **don't call save** — at
  flush (commit, before a query, or explicit `flush()`) Hibernate diffs against the snapshot and
  emits the UPDATE. There is no "save" step in JPA for already-managed entities.
- **Lazy vs eager:** to-many associations are LAZY by default; **to-one (`@ManyToOne`/`@OneToOne`)
  default to EAGER** — a common surprise. Lazy access requires an open context.
- **Mapping is bidirectional but has one owning side:** the owning side carries the FK / `@JoinColumn`;
  the inverse side uses `mappedBy`. Hibernate persists the relationship from the **owning side only**.
- **Spring Data repositories are an abstraction over the `EntityManager`** — derived/`@Query` methods,
  pagination, and transactions are conveniences; the JPA semantics underneath are unchanged.

## Headline gotchas / common mistakes

- **N+1 selects** — one query for parents, then one per child collection/association on access. The
  single most common JPA performance bug. Fix with a **fetch join**, **`@EntityGraph`**, or **batch
  fetching** (`@BatchSize` / `@Fetch(FetchMode.SUBSELECT)`) — not by flipping everything to EAGER.
  See repositories-queries.md.
- **`LazyInitializationException`** — touching a lazy association after the context/session closed
  (e.g. in a controller/view after the `@Transactional` service returned). Fix by fetching what you
  need *inside* the tx (fetch join / `@EntityGraph` / DTO projection) — **not** by reaching for
  Open-Session-In-View. See transactions.md.
- **Bidirectional relationships:** forgetting to set both sides, or a `toString()`/Jackson serializer
  that walks both sides → **infinite recursion / `StackOverflowError`**. Exclude the back-reference
  (`@JsonIgnore`/`@JsonManagedReference`/`@JsonBackReference`, or a DTO) and keep `equals`/`hashCode`
  off relationship fields.
- **`CascadeType.ALL` + `orphanRemoval = true`** surprises — `REMOVE` cascades to children, and
  removing a child from the collection (or reassigning it) deletes the row. Easy to delete more than
  intended. Cascade deliberately, per association.
- **`@Transactional` self-invocation** — calling a `@Transactional` method via `this.method()` from
  within the same bean bypasses the proxy, so propagation/rollback settings **do not apply**. The
  annotation also has no effect on private/`final`/package-private methods (proxy can't advise them).
- **`equals`/`hashCode` on entities** — don't use the auto-generated-`@Id` (it's null before persist,
  breaking `Set` membership across the persist boundary), and don't include all mutable fields. Use a
  stable business key, or a `UUID`/assigned id set at construction.
- **`FetchType.EAGER` defaults on `@ManyToOne`/`@OneToOne`** — eager fetches fire on every load, and
  multiple eager to-one associations on one entity can themselves create N+1 / cartesian blowups.
  Prefer LAZY and fetch explicitly where needed.

## Live docs protocol

For version-sensitive, provider-specific, or uncovered details:

1. **context7 MCP** (best for annotations/methods/config): Spring Data JPA is
   `/spring-projects/spring-data-jpa`, Hibernate ORM is `/hibernate/hibernate-orm`. If the context7
   tools aren't loaded, load them via ToolSearch
   (`select:mcp__plugin_context7_context7__resolve-library-id,mcp__plugin_context7_context7__query-docs`);
   `resolve-library-id` if those IDs don't resolve.
2. **WebFetch** `https://docs.spring.io/spring-data/jpa/reference/` (Spring Data JPA reference) and
   `https://hibernate.org/orm/documentation/` (Hibernate ORM user guide).
3. Cross-check the **jakarta vs javax** split and any annotation that may be Hibernate-only against
   the project's actual provider and version before recommending it.

Say when an answer is **verified-from-docs** vs **baked-in knowledge**. If the project's JPA/Hibernate
or Spring Data version differs from your assumptions, adapt and state what differs.
